1 olive oil
20 g butter
1.25 cup water (for the rice)
1 packet jasmine rice
1 capsicum
½ onion
1 bunch spring onion
¼ cup rice wine vinegar
1 packet ginger paste
2 tsp soy sauce
1 sachet mixed sesame seeds
¼ tsp salt
1 packet Roasted Peanuts & Cashew Mix
2 clove garlic
1 bag Asian Greens
¼ cup water (for the pickle)
1 packet Japanese Dressing
1 sachet Southeast Asian Spice Blend
1 packet Akaroa Salmon

Finely chop the garlic. In a large saucepan, melt the butter and a dash of olive oil over a medium heat. Cook the garlic until fragrant, 1-2 minutes. Add the water (for the rice) and a pinch of salt and bring to the boil. Add the jasmine rice, stir, cover with a lid and reduce the heat to low. Cook for 12 minutes, then remove the pan from the heat and keep covered until the rice is tender and all the water is absorbed, 10-15 minutes.

TIP: The rice will finish cooking in its own steam so don't peek!

While the rice is cooking, slice the capsicum into
thin strips. Roughly chop the Asian greens. Thinly
slice the red onion (see ingredients).

In a small bowl, combine the rice wine vinegar, water (for the pickle) and a generous pinch of salt and sugar. Stir to dissolve, then add the onion to the pickling liquid. Set aside.

In a large frying pan, heat a drizzle of olive oil over
a medium-high heat. Cook the capsicum with a
dash of water, tossing, until starting to soften,
3-4 minutes. Add the Asian greens and ginger
paste and cook until tender and fragrant,
1-2 minutes. Stir through the soy sauce and
Japanese dressing until warmed. Transfer to a
bowl.

While the veggies are cooking, combine the Southeast Asian spice blend, mixed sesame seeds and the salt in a shallow bowl. Pat the salmon dry with paper towel, drizzle with olive oil and season with salt and pepper. Press salmon into the sesame mixture and turn to coat on both sides. Return the frying pan to a medium heat with a drizzle of olive oil. When the oil is hot, cook the salmon, skin-side down, until just cooked through, 2-4 minutes each side (depending on thickness). Transfer to a plate to rest.

TIP: The spice blend will char slightly in the pan, this adds to the flavour!

Thinly slice the spring onion. Stir the spring
onion through the rice. Drain the pickled onion.
Divide the garlic rice between plates. Top with
the pickled onion, ginger-soy veggies and
sesame-crusted salmon. Garnish with the
roasted peanut & cashew mix to serve.